Load in required packages

In[1]:
import pandas as pd
from datetime import datetime, timedelta
import plotly.express as px
In[6]:
# Import CSV with renamed columns
df = pd.read_csv('bike_data.csv')
    
# Clean up some columns
df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["date"], format="%d/%m/%Y")
df["datetime"] = df.apply(
    lambda row: row["date"] + timedelta(hours=row["hour"]), axis=1
)
df["is_holiday"] = df["is_holiday"].map({"No Holiday": False, "Holiday": True})

# Similar to is_holiday, map is_functioning to True and False
df["is_functioning"] = df["is_functioning"].map({"Yes": True, "No": False})


# Only keep observations where the system is functioning
df = df[df["is_functioning"] == True]

# Print out the result
print(f"Dataset contains {len(df)} observations")

Dataset contains 8465 observations

Visualize bike rentals over time

In[7]:
# Create a line plot of rented bikes over time
fig = px.line(df, x="datetime", y="n_rented_bikes", 
              title="Hourly Bike Rentals Over Time")
fig.show()
In[8]:
# Calculate the total number of rented bikes per day
by_day = df \
    .groupby(by="date", as_index=False) \
    .agg({"n_rented_bikes": "sum"}) \
    [["date", "n_rented_bikes"]]

# Create a line plot showing total number of bikes per day over time
fig = px.line(by_day, x="date", y="n_rented_bikes",
              title="Daily Total Bike Rentals")
fig.show()
In[9]:
# Copy the previous chain of manipulations and add season as a variable to group by
by_day_season = df \
    .groupby(by=["date", "season"], as_index=False) \
    .agg({"n_rented_bikes": "sum"}) \
    [["date", "season", "n_rented_bikes"]]

# Copy the code for the previous line plot and map season to color
fig = px.line(by_day_season, x="date", y="n_rented_bikes", color="season",
              title="Daily Bike Rentals by Season")
fig.show()

Explore the relation between weather and rentals

In[13]:
# Query df to only keep observations at noon
noon_df = df.loc[df["hour"] == 12]

# Create a scatter plot showing temperature against number of rented bikes
fig = px.scatter(
    data_frame=noon_df,
    x="temperature_celsius",  # fixed column name
    y="n_rented_bikes",
    trendline="ols",
    title="Temperature vs Bike Rentals at Noon"
)
fig.show()
In[17]:
# Copy and update the code for the previous scatter plot 
# to investigate relation with other weather parameters
weather_vars = ["humidity_pct", "wind_speed_mps", "visibility_10m", 
                "dew_point_temp_c", "solar_radiation", "rainfall_mm", "snowfall_cm"]

for var in weather_vars:
    fig = px.scatter(noon_df, x=var, y="n_rented_bikes",
                     trendline="ols",
                     title=f"{var.replace('_', ' ').title()} vs Bike Rentals at Noon")
    fig.show()

Explore typical daily usage pattern

In[18]:
# Calculate the average number of rented bikes per hour
hourly_avg = df \
    .groupby(by="hour", as_index=False) \
    .agg({"n_rented_bikes": "mean"})

# Create a bar chart showing the usage pattern
fig = px.bar(hourly_avg, x="hour", y="n_rented_bikes",
             title="Average Hourly Bike Rentals")
fig.show()
In[19]:
# Copy and adapt the previous query to take into account the season
hourly_season_avg = df \
    .groupby(by=["hour", "season"], as_index=False) \
    .agg({"n_rented_bikes": "mean"})

# Copy and adapt the code for the previous bar chart to show usage pattern per season
fig = px.bar(hourly_season_avg, x="hour", y="n_rented_bikes",
             color="season", barmode="group",
             title="Average Hourly Bike Rentals by Season")
fig.show()

Extra: is New Year's Eve different?

In[20]:
# New Years dates
new_years_start = datetime(2017, 12, 31, 12)
new_years_end = datetime(2018, 1, 1, 12)

# Create data frame with new year's data
new_years_df = df[
    (df["datetime"] >= new_years_start) & 
    (df["datetime"] <= new_years_end)
]

# Show usage pattern
fig = px.line(new_years_df, x="datetime", y="n_rented_bikes",
              title="Bike Rentals During New Year's Eve")
fig.show()
